    "source": "the-wine-bible-karen-macneil.pdf_page_73",
    "contenu": "The document titled \"CLONES\" discusses the concept of grapevine clones in the context of winemaking. Here is a structured summary of its contents:\n\n### Title\n**CLONES**\n\n### Main Points\n1. **Variety in Grape Flavors**\n   - Different grape varieties like Chardonnay and Sauvignon Blanc have distinct tastes. However, even a single grape variety comprises numerous subtypes due to genetic mutations over time, which are identified as clones.\n   \n2. **Genetic Instability of Grapevines**\n   - Grapevines are not genetically stable and spontaneously mutate, creating a collection of subtypes known as clones. Each clone originates from a mother vine and is genetically identical to it. The propagation is typically through cuttings rather than seeds.\n   \n3. **Simplistic Example of Grapevine Clones**\n   - A hypothetical example involving two vineyards owned by Adam and Eve, and their son Abel, illustrates how a better-quality grapevine clone might be selected. Abel prefers his mother's vineyard and starts his own vineyard with cuttings from one of the superior grapevines from his mother’s vineyard, naming it “Eve’s Clone” of Pinot Noir.\n\n4. **Impact of Clones on Wine Quality**\n   - Clones can greatly influence the smell, taste, and overall quality of wine. Different clones of the same variety can produce wines with varying intensities of flavor, aromas, and tasting notes ranging from fruity to earthy.\n   - The choice of clone(s) by a producer significantly affects the wine’s ultimate flavor profile and character.\n\n### Conclusion\nThe document lays out how clones are a crucial factor in the diversity and quality of wines, emphasizing that grape varieties are more complex than they might seem due to the existence of these genetic variations."
