    "source": "mcgee.pdf_page_816",
    "contenu": "# The Four Basic Food Molecules\n\n## Introduction to Fat Behaviors\n\n- **Behavior in Baking**: Fat behavior in baking such as in butter is crucial for making pastries and cakes, aiding in their spreadability at room temperature.\n  \n- **Transformation of Fats**: Melted fats change from a liquid to a gas only under extremely high temperatures (from 500° to 750°F/260–400°C). This point is significantly above water’s boiling point due to the large molecular size of fats.\n\n## The Smoke Point of Fats\n- **Decomposition Point**: Fats begin to decompose at temperatures well below their boiling points and may spontaneously ignite when in contact with the stove’s gas flame.\n- **Maximum Temperature Limits**: The characteristic temperature where a fat breaks down into visible products is called the smoke point, where the fat also releases smoky fumes and various undesirable compounds.\n\n- **Impact of Free Fatty Acid Content**: The smoke point depends on the initial free fatty acid content of the fat; lower free fatty acid levels generally result in a higher and more stable smoke point.\n- **Example Refined Levels**: Refined vegetable oils have higher smoking points compared to unrefined ones or animal fats. Fresh refined vegetable oils begin to smoke around 410°F/230°C, whereas animal fats around 375°F/190°C.\n- **Usage Tip for Deep Frying**: The rate of fat breaking down during deep frying can be reduced by using a taller, narrow pan, thus minimizing the surface area of contact between the fat and the air.\n\n## Emulsifiers in Fats\n- **Type of Molecules**: Key emulsifiers in fat include **Phospholipids, Lecithin, Monoglycerides**.\n- **Functionality**: These molecules act as emulsifiers mixing oil and water components resulting in stable mixtures found in products like mayonnaise and hollandaise sauce.\n- **Structure and Behavior**: Lecithin, a predominant phospholipid, comprises a glycerol frame and constituents that give it a dual nature aiding in the emulsification process. The molecules have hydrophilic heads and hydrophobic tails, stabilizing emulsions.\n  \n- **Applications of Emulsifiers**: These \"surface-active\" molecules not only aid in emulsion but are also used extensively to enhance shelf life by preventing staling in baked products through interaction with starch molecules."
  },
