    "source": "mcgee.pdf_page_484",
    "contenu": "The given document is a section from a book focusing on \"SEEDS\" and includes in-depth information on barley, rye, and some pharmacological aspects related to rye. Below are the structured contents extracted and outlined according to the key topics covered in the document:\n\n### Barley Malt\n- **Form of Consumption**: The most common form in which barley is consumed is as **malt**.\n- **Uses**: Barley malt is primarily used in beers, some distilled liquors, and as a minor ingredient in baked goods.\n- **Preparation Process**: Malt is made from barley grains that are moistened and allowed to germinate. The process makes the grains sweet with sugars.\n- **Properties**: The detailed properties and qualities of barley malt are discussed on page 679 and 743 of the book.\n\n### Rye\n- **Origin**: Rye originated in southwest Asia, migrating with domesticated wheat and barley.\n- **Growth Conditions**: Rye thrives in cold climates like that around the Baltic Sea from around 2000 BCE. It grows well in poor, acidic and cool soils.\n- **Historical Importance**: It was a crucial bread grain for the poor in northern Europe and is still popular in regions like Poland and Germany.\n- **Height Adaptability**: Rye can grow as high as 12,000 feet.\n- **Production History**: In Germany, rye production historically exceeded wheat production for the first time in 1957.\n- **Chemical Composition**: Contains up to 70% of its weight in carbohydrates named pentosans, now referred to as arabinoxylans, which can absorb water and swell.\n\n### Rye and LSD\n- **Medical Implications**: Rye can indirectly influence modern medicine and pharmacology due to its suitability for the growth of ergot fungi (*Claviceps purpurea*), which has historical significance in medicine.\n- **Impact of Ergot**: Ergot contamination in rye was historically linked to ergotism or Saint Anthony’s Fire, causing symptoms like gangrene and mental derangement through the Middle Ages and up until the 20th century.\n- **Derivatives of Ergot**: Chemists in the early 20th century isolated several alkaloids from ergot, which vary from stimulating the uterus to causing hallucinations and constricting blood vessels.\n- **Significant Discovery**: In 1943, Albert Hofmann isolated LSD (lysergic acid diethylamide), an important pharmaceutical derivative of ergot, which became widely recognized in the 1960s.\n\nThese sections detail the significant aspects of barley and rye as food sources, their agricultural preferences, historical importance, and their indirect influence on medical pharmacology through secondary compounds like LSD."
  },
