    "source": "The_Art_of_Fermentation.pdf_page_266",
    "contenu": "The document describes a process for pickling plums using traditional Japanese methods. Below is the structured content of the process:\n\n---\n\n### Ingredients\n- 100 grams perilla leaves (about 50 leaves)\n- 2 tablespoons of sea salt\n- Plums (collected in mid-June when beginning to yellow but still green)\n\n### Process\n1. **Preparation**:\n   - Gather plums in mid-June.\n   - Wash plums thoroughly and soak overnight in clean water.\n\n2. **Draining and Setting Up**:\n   - Drain the plums and arrange them in a crock.\n   - Cover the plums with a heavy rock and allow the liquid to be drawn off by the salt for about 20 days.\n\n3. **Adding Perilla Leaves**:\n   - Remove the rock and cover from the crock.\n   - Drain the liquid (umeboshi vinegar) but keep it.\n   - Spread the plums out in the sun to dry, ideally in a single layer on baskets or screens, for two hot days.\n   - Mix the harvested perilla leaves with heaping tablespoons of salt and squeeze by hand to extract the purple liquid, which is discarded.\n\n4. **Returning Plums to Crock**:\n   - Return the plums to the crock.\n   - Pour back enough plum-vinegar to cover the plums completely.\n   - Seal the crock again.\n\n5. **Aging and Storage**:\n   - The following summer, remove the plums and dry them in the sun for one day.\n   - Store plums without vinegar in jars.\n   - The plums will become less salty and more delicious over time.\n\n### Notes\n- The plums used in this process are not fully ripe; they should be yellowing but still green.\n- It is essential to allow air circulation around the plums during sun drying.\n- The plums will disintegrate if they are fully ripe during the pickling process.\n- Each step involves careful handling to ensure proper flavors and preservation.\n\n---\n\nThis process results in traditional umeboshi, a preserved plum that is both a culinary and a cultural staple in Japan."
