    "contenu": "### Cooking Fish and Shellfish\n\n---\n\n#### Cooking Characteristics for Specific Fish\n- Cartilaginous sharks and skates benefit from higher temperatures and longer cooking to turn it into gelatin; they can be chewy unless cooked to 140°F/60°C or higher.\n- Some molluscs are rich in collagen and benefit from long cooking.\n\n#### Cooking Strategies\n- **Gentle Heat and Close Attention**: Fish easily overshoots the ideal temperature range for cooking. Whole fish and fillets have varying thicknesses which results in uneven cooking. Fish types like bluefish, tuna, swordfish, and shark contain dense flesh with high protein but lower fat content, making it easy to overcook the thinner areas while trying to cook the thicker sections.\n- **Workarounds for Uneven Cooking**:\n  - Use the gentlest possible heat.\n  - Oven baking and poaching are recommended low-temperature methods.\n  - After an initial high-temperature treatment, lower it to brown/sterilize the surfaces.\n  - Compensate for uneven thickness by cutting slashes in the thick areas every 1-2 cm.\n\n#### Monitoring Fish Doneness\n- Check fish early and often using timers, experience, and internal temperature measurements. Insert a thermometer, peek inside with a small incision, or use a skewer/ toothpick to check if the fish is translucent, if the connective tissue has dissolved, or if there’s resistance from coagulated muscle fibers.\n\n#### Special Cooking Concerns for Mushy Fish\n- **Why Fish Can Become Mushy**: In certain fish like Atlantic salmon, slow cooking can lead to mushiness caused by protein-digesting enzymes active at around 130-140°F/55-60°C. These enzymes break down muscle cells into energy, increasing as the temperature rises.\n- **Prevention**: Fish prone to becoming mushy such as salmon are best cooked quickly to a high temperature to kill the enzymes, ideally at 160°F/70°C or lower but served immediately after.\n\n#### Preparations for Cooking\n- **Cleaning and Cutting**: In U.S. markets, fish are often sold precleaned and precut."
